      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — approx 7–9 seconds long.\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps.\n* Lighting & Color: Gym or clean indoor-home environment; neutral background; soft key-light + ambient fill so arms, elbows, torso posture and weight path are clearly visible.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (dumbbell/cable noise, subtle breathing), no voice-over (optionally gentle inhale/exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym or home-gym space, free weights (dumbbell or kettlebell) or cable machine (with rope/handle) available. Enough vertical clearance overhead; floor clear of obstacles.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or waist-height), capturing full upper body (head to hips/waist) — to show torso alignment, arm path, elbow position, and shoulder posture.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts or training pants), ready to perform the exercise.\nAction / Beats (0 s–~9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position:\n* If using a dumbbell: hold a single dumbbell overhead with both hands (cupping the end), arms fully extended. Or if using two dumbbells: each hand gripping a dumbbell, but overhead. Arms vertical, elbows close (not flared), core braced, spine neutral, chest up.\n* If using cable: set up pulley such that rope/handle is overhead (or slightly behind), grasp handles with both hands (or single arm variation), stand upright (or seated) with core tight, shoulders stable.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Engage core, brace glutes, keep shoulders down (not shrugged), maintain upright posture; ensure upper arms remain nearly stationary (only forearms move).\n* 2–4 s — Eccentric Phase (Lowering): Inhale; slowly bend your elbows and lower the weight/cable behind your head, allowing forearms to move while upper arms stay roughly fixed. Lower until elbows approach ~90°, or until you feel a firm stretch in the triceps — but avoid letting upper arms shift backward too much.\n* 4–5 s — Bottom / Stretch & Pause: Brief pause (~0.2–0.4 s) at bottom — weight behind head, elbows bent, triceps stretched; maintain torso stability, posture controlled.\n* 5–7 s — Concentric Phase (Press Up): Exhale; extend elbows, pressing the weight upward back to full extension overhead, keeping upper arms nearly still; wrists/elbows aligned over shoulders.\n* 7–8/9 s — Lockout / Reset: Arms fully extended overhead, shoulders stable, core engaged; hold briefly (0.2–0.3 s), then lower weight if continuing or finish the clip.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Triceps brachii — all heads (long, medial, lateral) are activated, with particular emphasis on the long head, which is stretched when arms are overhead.\n* Shoulder-girdle stabilizers & core muscles — because the arms are overhead, shoulder stabilizers and core (abs, obliques, lower back) work to maintain posture and joint stability.\nBenefits of Overhead Triceps Extension\n* Excellent as an isolation movement for triceps, ensuring elbows do the movement (not shoulders or chest), promoting growth and definition of the back of the arms.\n* Long-head emphasis: Because the long head attaches to the shoulder blade and crosses the shoulder joint, overhead positioning gives it a greater stretch — favorable for hypertrophy and fuller arm development.\n* Joint — and torso-friendly (compared with heavy presses): Since this is an elbow-extension exercise (single-joint), it doesn’t heavily load shoulders or spine; useful for isolating triceps without stressing joints or chest.\n* Good accessibility and variation: Works with dumbbells, cables, bands — can be done standing, seated, or even single-arm. Useful for home or gym.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep upper arms fixed — only forearms move: Avoid letting elbows drift backward or outward; maintain elbows close to keep tension on triceps.\n* Use controlled tempo — especially lowering (eccentric): Slow descent ensures deep stretch, better tension, and reduces risk of joint stress.\n* Core and trunk stable: Brace abs/glutes to avoid arching lower back; overhead weight plus lax core can strain spine.\n* Choose appropriate weight: Because of stretch and joint position, don’t overload — use weight you can control through full range.\n* Avoid flaring elbows or letting them drift: Flared elbows shift stress away from triceps to shoulders/elbows — reduces effectiveness and increases injury risk.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Triceps brachii — all heads (long, medial, lateral) are activated, with particular emphasis on the long head, which is stretched when arms are overhead.\n* Shoulder-girdle stabilizers & core muscles — because the arms are overhead, shoulder stabilizers and core (abs, obliques, lower back) work to maintain posture and joint stability.",
      "benefits": "of Overhead Triceps Extension\n* Excellent as an isolation movement for triceps, ensuring elbows do the movement (not shoulders or chest), promoting growth and definition of the back of the arms.\n* Long-head emphasis: Because the long head attaches to the shoulder blade and crosses the shoulder joint, overhead positioning gives it a greater stretch — favorable for hypertrophy and fuller arm development.\n* Joint — and torso-friendly (compared with heavy presses): Since this is an elbow-extension exercise (single-joint), it doesn’t heavily load shoulders or spine; useful for isolating triceps without stressing joints or chest.\n* Good accessibility and variation: Works with dumbbells, cables, bands — can be done standing, seated, or even single-arm. Useful for home or gym.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips\n* Keep upper arms fixed — only forearms move: Avoid letting elbows drift backward or outward; maintain elbows close to keep tension on triceps.\n* Use controlled tempo — especially lowering (eccentric): Slow descent ensures deep stretch, better tension, and reduces risk of joint stress.\n* Core and trunk stable: Brace abs/glutes to avoid arching lower back; overhead weight plus lax core can strain spine.\n* Choose appropriate weight: Because of stretch and joint position, don’t overload — use weight you can control through full range.\n* Avoid flaring elbows or letting them drift: Flared elbows shift stress away from triceps to shoulders/elbows — reduces effectiveness and increases injury risk."
