      "id": "arms_bicep_curl_male",
      "name": "Bicep Curl",
      "gender": "male",
      "category": "arms",
      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — about 7–9 seconds long.\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps.\n* Lighting & Color: Gym or home-gym lighting; neutral or minimal background to highlight arms, dumbbells/barbell and posture; soft key-light + ambient fill so muscle contraction and motion are clearly visible.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (dumbbell/barbell movement, subtle breathing), no voice-over (optional soft inhale/exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Equipment: Dumbbells or barbell (or even cable machine), depending on variation. Floor clear, stable footing, good vertical space.\n* Location: Gym floor or home-gym area; enough space to stand upright.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or waist-height) capturing head-to-feet — to see foot stance, posture, arm path, and full movement.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/ pants), holding weight(s) at sides (starting position), ready to curl.\nAction / Beats (0 s–~9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position: Subject stands upright, feet about hip- or shoulder-width apart (slight bend in knees optional), core braced, spine neutral. Hold dumbbell(s) (or barbell) in arms extended by thighs, palms facing forward (supinated grip) or inward depending on variation. Elbows kept close to torso, shoulder blades pulled slightly back/down to stabilize shoulder girdle.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Engage core, keep torso still (no swinging or swaying), ensure elbows stay fixed at sides (not drifting forward/back). This ensures the load remains on biceps, not shoulders or back.\n* 2–4 s — Curl / Concentric Phase: Exhale; curl the weight upward by bending the elbows — raise forearms toward shoulders while keeping upper arms stationary. Continue until forearms near shoulders (or full flexion), squeezing the biceps at the top for a brief moment.\n* 4–5 s — Peak / Hold: Pause ~0.2–0.4 s at the top — full elbow flexion, biceps fully contracted, maintain stable posture. This “peak contraction” helps maximize muscle engagement.\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly lower the weight back to the starting position (arms extended), controlling the descent, maintaining elbow alignment, posture stable — avoid “letting go” of weight or using momentum.\n* 7–8/9 s — Reset / Ready: Arms back at sides, posture stable — ready for next rep or clip fade-out.\nMuscles / Focus (What Bicep Curl Works)\n* Primary target: Biceps brachii — the main “show-muscle” on the front of upper arm, responsible for elbow flexion and forearm supination.\n* Supporting muscles:\n* Brachialis — beneath the biceps, contributes to elbow flexion and adds arm thickness.\n* Brachioradialis (forearm) — engaged to assist in elbow flexion and stabilize the forearm during the curl.\n* Forearm & grip muscles — they help stabilize the weight.\nBenefits & Why Use Bicep Curl\n* Effective arm isolation and hypertrophy: By focusing on elbow flexion and minimizing involvement of larger muscles or momentum, curls help build biceps size and definition.\n* Enhances arm strength and functional elbow flexion — useful for pulling/lifting tasks that rely on bent-arm strength.\n* Improves arm symmetry and muscular balance — dumbbell versions especially help if one arm is weaker, by forcing each arm to work independently.\n* Easy to customize & vary: Use dumbbells, barbell, cables, change grip width or hand orientation (supinated / neutral / pronated) to emphasize different muscle heads (biceps long vs short head, brachialis, forearms).\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep elbows stationary at sides, resist swinging or using momentum — movement should come from elbow flexion not torso/back.\n* Use full range of motion — extend arms fully at bottom and flex fully at top to maximize muscle stretch and contraction.\n* Choose appropriate weight — heavy enough to challenge but light enough to maintain form; avoid “ego lifting.”\n* Maintain neutral spine, stable posture, core engaged — avoid leaning back or swinging body to help lift weight.\n* Control both phases — slow eccentric (lowering) as well as controlled concentric (lifting) for better muscle engagement and reduced joint stress.",
