      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional clip — about 7–9 seconds long.\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps.\n* Lighting & Color: Clean indoor gym / home-floor lighting; neutral or minimal background to highlight body posture and movement clearly. Soft key-light + ambient fill to emphasize body alignment and muscle action.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (floor contact, subtle breathing), no voice-over (optionally gentle inhale-exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Flat floor or mat (gym or home), clear space around.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) capturing full body — from head to heels — so you see alignment, arm path, torso, and leg posture.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, wearing workout clothes (t-shirt/tank + shorts or training pants), ready to perform push-up.\nAction / Beats (0 s–~9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position:\n* Hands placed on floor slightly wider than shoulder-width, palms flat; toes on floor, body extended — full-body plank: head to heels in a straight line. Core engaged, glutes & legs slightly tensed, shoulders stable.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Engage core, tighten glutes and leg muscles. Keep body rigid and spine neutral, gaze slightly forward/down to keep neck in line. Elbows slightly bent, ready to descend.\n* 2–4 s — Lower / Descent Phase (Eccentric): Inhale; bend elbows to lower your chest toward the floor in a controlled motion. Keep elbows at a safe angle (not flared excessively), body straight without sagging hips or raised butt. Lower until chest is close to floor (or until elbows ~90°), controlling descent smoothly.\n* 4–5 s — Touch / Pause (optional): Brief pause (~0.1–0.3 s) near bottom — maintain tension, avoid resting weight (no “collapse”).\n* 5–7 s — Push / Concentric Phase: Exhale; press through palms to straighten arms, pushing your body up back to start position. Keep body aligned — head-to-heels straight, core engaged, glutes tight, avoid sagging or arching.\n* 7–8/9 s — Lockout / Reset: Arms extended, body aligned, slight pause (~0.2 s) at top, then fade out or hold for next rep.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus (What Push-up Works)\n* Chest (pectoralis major, minor) — primary pushing muscles.\n* Shoulders (deltoids — especially front + some medial involvement) — assist in stabilising and pushing.\n* Triceps (back of arms) — extend elbows during push-up.\n* Core muscles (abdominals, transverse abdominis, spinal stabilisers) — engaged to keep spine neutral, maintain plank posture.\n* Lower-body stabilisers (glutes, quads, hip muscles) — help keep body rigid, support correct alignment during the movement.\n* Stabiliser muscles (shoulder-girdle, rotator-cuff, serratus, forearms/wrists) — involved to support joint alignment, stabilize body under load.\nBenefits & Why Use Push-up\n* Efficient upper-body strength builder: chest, shoulders, triceps all get worked with one exercise.\n* Core, posture & full-body stability: because you maintain a plank throughout, your core and stabiliser muscles get trained — helps improve posture and body control.\n* Convenient & equipment-free: requires no weights or machines — you can do push-ups almost anywhere.\n* Cardiovascular & body-composition benefits: when done in volume or as part of circuit, push-ups increase heart rate, help burn calories, and support fat-loss + lean-mass gains.\n* Versatile & scalable: many variations (incline, decline, narrow, wide, diamond, knee-push, etc.) let you adjust difficulty or target slightly different muscles.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep body in straight line from head to heels — no sagging hips or raised butt. Engage core, glutes, legs.\n* Place hands just slightly wider than shoulder-width, and ensure they’re under shoulders to avoid undue shoulder strain.\n* Keep elbows at safe angle — not flared out wide; ideally around 45–70° relative to torso — protects shoulders, engages muscles effectively.\n* Control both descent and ascent — avoid “dropping” down or “bouncing” at bottom; controlled motion ensures muscle activation and reduces injury risk.\n* Breathe properly — inhale while lowering, exhale while pushing up. Maintain stable core and avoid neck strain (gaze slightly forward or down).If standard push-ups are too hard, start with easier variations (e.g. incline push-up, knee push-up) — you can progress gradually.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "(What Push-up Works)\n* Chest (pectoralis major, minor) — primary pushing muscles.\n* Shoulders (deltoids — especially front + some medial involvement) — assist in stabilising and pushing.\n* Triceps (back of arms) — extend elbows during push-up.\n* Core muscles (abdominals, transverse abdominis, spinal stabilisers) — engaged to keep spine neutral, maintain plank posture.\n* Lower-body stabilisers (glutes, quads, hip muscles) — help keep body rigid, support correct alignment during the movement.\n* Stabiliser muscles (shoulder-girdle, rotator-cuff, serratus, forearms/wrists) — involved to support joint alignment, stabilize body under load.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Push-up\n* Efficient upper-body strength builder: chest, shoulders, triceps all get worked with one exercise.\n* Core, posture & full-body stability: because you maintain a plank throughout, your core and stabiliser muscles get trained — helps improve posture and body control.\n* Convenient & equipment-free: requires no weights or machines — you can do push-ups almost anywhere.\n* Cardiovascular & body-composition benefits: when done in volume or as part of circuit, push-ups increase heart rate, help burn calories, and support fat-loss + lean-mass gains.\n* Versatile & scalable: many variations (incline, decline, narrow, wide, diamond, knee-push, etc.) let you adjust difficulty or target slightly different muscles.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips\n* Keep body in straight line from head to heels — no sagging hips or raised butt. Engage core, glutes, legs.\n* Place hands just slightly wider than shoulder-width, and ensure they’re under shoulders to avoid undue shoulder strain.\n* Keep elbows at safe angle — not flared out wide; ideally around 45–70° relative to torso — protects shoulders, engages muscles effectively.\n* Control both descent and ascent — avoid “dropping” down or “bouncing” at bottom; controlled motion ensures muscle activation and reduces injury risk.\n* Breathe properly — inhale while lowering, exhale while pushing up. Maintain stable core and avoid neck strain (gaze slightly forward or down).If standard push-ups are too hard, start with easier variations (e.g. incline push-up, knee push-up) — you can progress gradually."
