      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult female, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "(What Side Lateral Raise Works)\n* Lateral (medial) head of the deltoid — the main target; responsible for shoulder abduction (lifting arms sideways), giving shoulder width and that “cap” look.\n* Supporting muscles:\n* Anterior and posterior deltoid heads (assist/stabilize)\n* Upper-back / trapezius muscles and scapular stabilizers — for shoulder-blade stabilization during movement.\n* Core — to maintain upright posture and prevent torso sway or compensation.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Side Lateral Raise\n* Helps build shoulder width / better upper-body proportions — developing the lateral delts contributes significantly to broader shoulders and more defined upper-body silhouette.\n* Promotes balanced shoulder development — many compound lifts emphasize front delts or pressing motion; lateral raises ensure the lateral (and to some extent posterior) delts are not neglected.\n* Effective isolation movement — reduces reliance on larger muscle groups or momentum; good for hypertrophy (muscle growth) and detail work.\n* Improves shoulder stability and posture — strengthening deltoid + stabilizers helps maintain shoulder health, balance, and posture (useful if you sit a lot / have desk job).\n* Accessible & Equipment-Light — only requires dumbbells (or light weights); you can even do variations with lighter weights, bands or cables if needed.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips & Common Mistakes\n* Use light to moderate weight — lateral deltoids are relatively small muscles; heavy dumbbells often force momentum or shrugging, reducing effectiveness and risking shoulder stress.\n* Lead with elbows, not wrists — elbow should rise first; wrists follow; this ensures the load stays on deltoids, not forearms or traps.\n* Keep slight elbow bend throughout; don’t lock elbows straight — this reduces joint stress and maintains tension on delts.\n* Don’t lift beyond shoulder-height — raising arms too high shifts emphasis to traps and increases risk of joint impingement. Stop when arms are roughly parallel to floor.\n* Avoid swinging or using torso momentum — movement should be slow, controlled; core engaged, torso stable. If you struggle, switching to seated lateral raises helps minimize momentum."
