      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional clip — ~ 8–10 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym or home-gym lighting; a clean background (bench, floor, plain wall) with soft key-light + fill light to clearly highlight arms, weight path, and torso alignment.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (weight bar/dumbbell sound, subtle floor or bench noise, breathing), no voice-over (optionally light inhale/exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Flat bench (or floor if bench unavailable) with adequate vertical clearance. Floor/bench area clear of clutter.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or at torso level) capturing from head to hips — to show bench, upper-body posture, arm path, and elbow/shoulder position.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout attire (tank/tee + shorts or gym pants), lying supine on bench, holding weight (barbell or dumbbells), ready for extension.\nAction / Beats (0 s–~9–10 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position: Lie flat on bench (or floor), feet flat on floor, back and glutes pressed – core engaged. Hold the barbell or dumbbells above chest/shoulders with arms extended, elbows locked or slightly soft — this is start. Keep wrists straight, grip firm.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Slightly retract shoulder blades into bench, engage core & glutes, stabilize upper arms — ensure upper arms stay vertical relative to torso, elbows positioned roughly shoulder-width.\n* 2–4 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; bend elbows to slowly lower the weight toward forehead/top of head (or just behind head depending on flexibility), ensuring upper arms stay fixed (only forearms move). Keep movement controlled.\n* 4–5 s — Bottom / Stretch & Pause: Pause briefly (~ 0.2–0.5 s) at the bottom — weight near head, triceps under stretch. Elbows remain steady; don’t let them flare out.\n* 5–7 s — Press / Concentric Phase: Exhale; extend elbows to press the weight back up overhead / back to starting position, using triceps — keep upper arms fixed, avoid using shoulders/back.\n* 7–9/10 s — Lockout / Reset: Arms extended overhead or slightly forward, maintaining tension in triceps, stable posture; hold briefly (~0.2 s) then prepare for next rep or fade out.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Triceps Brachii — All three heads (long, medial, lateral) are engaged, with emphasis on the long head especially because the arm is raised overhead relative to torso.\n* Stabilizers & Support Muscles: Shoulder-girdle stabilizers, forearm/wrist muscles for grip, core/spinal stabilizers for back support on bench, and glutes/legs (feet anchored) to maintain stable base.\nWhy Use Lying Triceps Extension — Benefits\n* Highly effective triceps isolation & hypertrophy — allows targeted work on the triceps, especially the long head, promoting size and strength in the back of the arms.\n* Full range-of-motion & stretch — lowering weight behind head gives a deep stretch, often more effective than standing extensions, which can help with muscle growth.\n* Better control and joint-friendly — lying position stabilizes body and reduces lower-back strain; elbows stay fixed, reducing turnover from shoulders/back and minimizing risk when done with good form.\n* Balances arm development — complements compound pushing exercises (bench press, shoulder press) by isolating elbow-extension strength and improving overall arm definition and strength.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips & Common Mistakes\n* Keep upper arms fixed & elbows tight — avoid letting elbows flare; forearms should move while upper arms stay vertical.\n* Use a controlled tempo — especially on the lowering phase; avoid dropping weight or using momentum, which reduces triceps engagement and increases injury risk.\n* Avoid excessive back arch — maintain contact between upper/mid-back and bench, engage core and glutes; don't let ribcage flare or lower back over-arch.\n* Choose weight appropriately — use light to moderate load to maintain control, full range of motion, good form; prioritize triceps contraction over heavy weight.\n* Mind elbow placement — starting position elbows shoulder-width; lowering should bring weight close to forehead/top-of-head, not far forward or behind to avoid undue shoulder/elbow stress.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Triceps Brachii — All three heads (long, medial, lateral) are engaged, with emphasis on the long head especially because the arm is raised overhead relative to torso.\n* Stabilizers & Support Muscles: Shoulder-girdle stabilizers, forearm/wrist muscles for grip, core/spinal stabilizers for back support on bench, and glutes/legs (feet anchored) to maintain stable base.",
      "benefits": "Lying Triceps Extension — Benefits\n* Highly effective triceps isolation & hypertrophy — allows targeted work on the triceps, especially the long head, promoting size and strength in the back of the arms.\n* Full range-of-motion & stretch — lowering weight behind head gives a deep stretch, often more effective than standing extensions, which can help with muscle growth.\n* Better control and joint-friendly — lying position stabilizes body and reduces lower-back strain; elbows stay fixed, reducing turnover from shoulders/back and minimizing risk when done with good form.\n* Balances arm development — complements compound pushing exercises (bench press, shoulder press) by isolating elbow-extension strength and improving overall arm definition and strength.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips & Common Mistakes\n* Keep upper arms fixed & elbows tight — avoid letting elbows flare; forearms should move while upper arms stay vertical.\n* Use a controlled tempo — especially on the lowering phase; avoid dropping weight or using momentum, which reduces triceps engagement and increases injury risk.\n* Avoid excessive back arch — maintain contact between upper/mid-back and bench, engage core and glutes; don't let ribcage flare or lower back over-arch.\n* Choose weight appropriately — use light to moderate load to maintain control, full range of motion, good form; prioritize triceps contraction over heavy weight.\n* Mind elbow placement — starting position elbows shoulder-width; lowering should bring weight close to forehead/top-of-head, not far forward or behind to avoid undue shoulder/elbow stress."
