      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — about 7–9 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym or home-gym with cable/pulley machine visible; clean background or slightly out-of-focus to keep emphasis on body posture, arms & movement. Soft key-light + fill light to highlight arm extension path and muscle engagement.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (cable noise, slight weight stack sound, breathing), no voice-over (optional subtle inhale/exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Standing in front of a cable-pulley machine set with a bar, rope, or suitable handle at chest–head height. Floor clear, proper stance, stable footing.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or at waist-height), capturing from head to thighs — enough to see torso posture, elbow/wrist alignment, cable/handle, and full arm motion.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, average/athletic build, wearing gym clothes (tank/tee + shorts or pants), gripping the cable attachment/custom handle, ready to push down.\nAction / Beats (0 s–~9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position: Stand upright facing cable machine. Grasp the bar (or rope/handle) with overhand grip (or neutral if rope). Elbows close to sides, forearms vertical, upper arms nearly stationary, core engaged, back straight.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Slight bend in knees, feet about hip-width. Shoulders down/back, chest up, core braced — ensure no forward lean or excessive torso sway. Elbows pinned beside torso.\n* 2–4 s — Push / Concentric Phase: Exhale; extend elbows to push the handle downward until arms are fully extended (wrists and elbows aligned, forearms roughly vertical). Keep upper arms fixed by sides — movement originates at elbows. 4–5 s — Lockout / Squeeze: Brief pause (~0.2–0.5 s) at bottom — arms extended, triceps contracted, feel full triceps tension. Maintain posture.\n* 5–7 s — Return / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly allow forearms to return upward to starting position with control — avoid letting weights snap back. Keep elbows close; maintain core and posture.\n* 7–9 s — Reset / Ready for Next Rep or Clip End: Arms vertical, elbows by sides, torso stable — ready for next repetition or fade out.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus (What Push-down Works)\n* Triceps brachii — the main target. The push-down isolates elbow-extension, engaging all three heads: lateral, medial, and long head. Especially effective for the lateral and medial heads.\n* Secondary / Supportive Muscles: Forearms (for grip/stabilization), shoulder-girdle stabilizers (to keep elbows fixed), core & lower-body stabilizers (to maintain posture).\nWhy Use Push-down — Key Benefits\n* Highly effective isolation exercise for triceps — good for building arm size and definition without involving large muscle groups like back or chest.\n* Offers constant tension throughout motion (especially with cable) — helps maximize muscle activation and hypertrophy.\n* Versatile variation possibilities: rope, straight bar, V-bar, underhand or overhand grips, even resistance-band versions make it adaptable to different gym setups and joint comfort levels.\n* Easy to control form and tempo — relatively simple to execute properly, making it suitable for beginners and advanced trainees alike.\nCommon Mistakes / Form & Safety Tips\n* Keep elbows pinned by sides — don’t let them drift forward/back or flare out; movement should come from the elbows, not shoulders.\n* Use controlled motion — avoid swinging, using momentum, or letting weight stack slam back up. Controlled eccentric helps maximize muscle tension and prevent injury.\n* Proper posture — stand upright, core braced, slight knee bend; don’t lean excessively forward/backward to “cheat.”\n* Select appropriate weight and attachment — heavy loads often compromise form; rope or V-bar often easier on wrists/shoulders and better for muscle targeting.",
