      "id": "arms_diamond_push_up_male",
      "name": "Diamond Push-Up",
      "gender": "male",
      "category": "arms",
      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic/instructional strength-clip — about 7–9 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Colour: Simple indoor/gym-floor or home mat; neutral background; soft key-light + ambient fill so body alignment, hands, core and arm motion are clearly visible\n* Sound: Quiet ambient (floor contact, slight shifting, breathing), no voice-over (optionally subtle breath sounds)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Flat floor or exercise mat — enough space in front + overhead clearance.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) capturing full body from head to heels — to show plank alignment, hand position, arm path, and body posture.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts or training pants), ready to perform push-up.\nAction / Beats (0–~9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup (Top / Plank Position): Subject assumes a high-plank: feet on toes, body straight from head to heels, core & glutes engaged, legs tight, shoulders over hands. Hands are brought together under chest so that thumbs and index fingers touch — forming a “diamond” shape. Hands slightly ahead of sternum (not under shoulders as in regular push-up).\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Stabilize: Engage core, glutes, quads; keep spine neutral; shoulder blades slightly pulled down/back; elbows ready but tucked close to torso (not flared).\n* 2–4 s — Descent (Eccentric Phase): Inhale; bend elbows while keeping them close to sides; lower your chest toward the “diamond” hands — the chest moves toward the floor just above/near hands. Keep body straight, avoid sagging hips or raised butt.\n* 4–5 s — Bottom / Pause (Optional): Pause briefly (e.g. 0.2–0.4 s) when chest is low — hold tension in arms, triceps, shoulders, core.\n* 5–7 s — Push / Concentric Phase: Exhale; press through palms, extend elbows to raise body back to plank/top position (arms near-extended), while keeping body rigid and aligned.\n* 7–8/9 s — Reset / Ready: Body straight, hands in diamond position, core engaged — ready for next rep or fade-out.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus (What Diamond Push-Up Works)\n* Triceps (especially lateral/medial/long heads): The close, diamond-hand placement shifts emphasis strongly onto the triceps — much more than a standard wide or regular push-up.\n* Chest (pectoralis major & minor): Works the chest, though less than standard push-up — still contributes, especially the inner chest region.\n* Shoulders (deltoids, front head primarily): Shoulder joint supports pressing motion and stabilizes under narrower hand-base.\n* Core, abs, glutes, legs & stabilizers: Because body must remain a rigid plank while performing — core, glutes, hips, legs keep alignment — adding a stability and full-body control component.\nWhy Use Diamond Push-Up — Key Benefits\n* Strong triceps development & arm definition: By shifting load away from chest and onto triceps, diamond push-ups are among the most effective body-weight moves for rear-arm strength/hypertrophy.\n* Core & full-body stabilization challenge: Keeping the body tight in a narrow-hand plank forces core, glutes, legs, and stabilizing muscles to stay active — beneficial for overall functional strength and posture.\n* No equipment needed / Anywhere-friendly: As a pure body-weight movement, you can perform diamond push-ups anywhere — home, outdoors, while traveling — no need for weights or machines.\n* Good pressing strength carryover: Builds pressing and elbow-extension strength, useful for dips, overhead presses, other upper-body pushing movements.\n* Variation & versatility: Can progress or regress according to ability — from knee or incline diamond push-ups to weighted or elevated versions — making it adaptable across experience levels.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips & Common Mistakes\n* Keep hands forming a clean diamond — thumbs + index fingers touching, placed roughly under the sternum or just below chest, not too far forward/back. Over-narrow or improper hand placement can strain wrists or shoulders.\n* Maintain a straight body line (plank posture) — no sagging hips, no raised butt, no rounding or arching of spine. Engage core, glutes, quads.\n* Keep elbows tucked and close to sides, not flared — this maximizes triceps activation and reduces stress on shoulders.\n* Move in controlled tempo — descent and ascent should be deliberate and steady; avoid bouncing or jerking, especially at bottom where stress on elbows/shoulders increases.\n* If full-body diamond push-ups are too challenging, regress or modify: options include knee diamond push-ups, incline diamond push-ups (hands on elevated surface), or narrow-hand standard push-ups — helps build strength progressively.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "(What Diamond Push-Up Works)\n* Triceps (especially lateral/medial/long heads): The close, diamond-hand placement shifts emphasis strongly onto the triceps — much more than a standard wide or regular push-up.\n* Chest (pectoralis major & minor): Works the chest, though less than standard push-up — still contributes, especially the inner chest region.\n* Shoulders (deltoids, front head primarily): Shoulder joint supports pressing motion and stabilizes under narrower hand-base.\n* Core, abs, glutes, legs & stabilizers: Because body must remain a rigid plank while performing — core, glutes, hips, legs keep alignment — adding a stability and full-body control component.",
      "benefits": "Diamond Push-Up — Key Benefits\n* Strong triceps development & arm definition: By shifting load away from chest and onto triceps, diamond push-ups are among the most effective body-weight moves for rear-arm strength/hypertrophy.\n* Core & full-body stabilization challenge: Keeping the body tight in a narrow-hand plank forces core, glutes, legs, and stabilizing muscles to stay active — beneficial for overall functional strength and posture.\n* No equipment needed / Anywhere-friendly: As a pure body-weight movement, you can perform diamond push-ups anywhere — home, outdoors, while traveling — no need for weights or machines.\n* Good pressing strength carryover: Builds pressing and elbow-extension strength, useful for dips, overhead presses, other upper-body pushing movements.\n* Variation & versatility: Can progress or regress according to ability — from knee or incline diamond push-ups to weighted or elevated versions — making it adaptable across experience levels.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips & Common Mistakes\n* Keep hands forming a clean diamond — thumbs + index fingers touching, placed roughly under the sternum or just below chest, not too far forward/back. Over-narrow or improper hand placement can strain wrists or shoulders.\n* Maintain a straight body line (plank posture) — no sagging hips, no raised butt, no rounding or arching of spine. Engage core, glutes, quads.\n* Keep elbows tucked and close to sides, not flared — this maximizes triceps activation and reduces stress on shoulders.\n* Move in controlled tempo — descent and ascent should be deliberate and steady; avoid bouncing or jerking, especially at bottom where stress on elbows/shoulders increases.\n* If full-body diamond push-ups are too challenging, regress or modify: options include knee diamond push-ups, incline diamond push-ups (hands on elevated surface), or narrow-hand standard push-ups — helps build strength progressively."
