      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — ~ 8–10 seconds long.\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps.\n* Lighting & Color: Gym environment (or home gym), simple/clean background, subtle key-light + ambient fill to highlight back, arm, and barbell motion distinctly.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (barbell sliding/plate sound, subtle floor/foot noise, breathing), no voice-over (or optional gentle breath-in/exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Equipment: Barbell with weight plates, flat floor; possibly a rack to load/unload.\n* Location: Gym or home-gym; enough space to hinge forward safely; floor clear of obstacles.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or at torso-height) capturing from head to feet — so hips, torso angle, back alignment, bar path, arm motion, and foot stance are visible.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult female, athletic or average build, wearing gym clothes, gripping barbell, ready to perform bent-over row.\nAction / Beats (0–~9/10 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position: Stand with feet roughly hip- to shoulder-width apart. Grip barbell with pronated (overhand) grip just outside thighs. Hinge at hips, push butt slightly back, bend knees a bit, and lean torso forward until it’s angled (often ~45–60°), keeping back flat/neutral, chest up, core engaged, head/neck in line with spine. Arms extended downward, barbell hanging.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Pre-tension: Brace core and glutes, keep spine neutral, shoulder blades slightly retracted/down to stabilize shoulder girdle. Barbell should hang freely, weight balanced.\n* 2–4 s — Row / Concentric Phase: Exhale; pull the barbell upward towards lower abdomen or waist — leading with elbows pulling back (not lifting with arms), contracting back muscles (lats, middle back, traps), keeping torso stable (no jerking or swaying).\n* 4–5 s — Peak / Squeeze: Pause briefly (~0.2–0.5 s) at top — bar close to body, shoulder-blades squeezed together, back muscles engaged; demonstrate full contraction.\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly lower the barbell back toward starting position, arms extending downward, back stable, maintaining flat spine and tension in posterior chain. Avoid dropping weight or “bouncing.”\n* 7–9/10 s — Reset / Ready: Return to hinge-forward starting position, bar hanging, posture stable — ready for next rep or clip end.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus (What Back Rows Work)\n* Back muscles: Mainly Latissimus dorsi (lats), Rhomboids, and Trapezius (middle/lower), which generate the pulling motion and are responsible for upper-back width and thickness.\n* Posterior deltoids (rear shoulders) — engaged especially during the row’s retraction and scapular-retraction phases.\n* Stabilizers & supporting muscles: Lower back (spinal erectors), core muscles, glutes and hamstrings — to maintain torso position and stability during the bent-over posture.\n* Arms (to a lesser extent): Biceps and forearms contribute to grip and assist in pulling, but they are secondary to the back muscles.\nWhy Use Back Rows — Benefits\n* Effective for building back size (mass) and strength — back rows allow substantial loading and target large back muscles, contributing to thickness and a strong posterior chain.\n* Helps improve posture and spinal health — strengthening the posterior chain (back, glutes, spine-stabilizers) can alleviate back-pain risk, improve posture, and support day-to-day movements.\n* Functional pulling strength — helps in movements that require pulling force (lifting, carrying, climbing, daily tasks), not just aesthetic benefit.\n* Versatile — can be performed with barbell, dumbbells, or as supported (one-arm or bench-supported) rows depending on available equipment and user’s comfort / back health.\nForm & Safety / Technique & Considerations\n* Maintain a flat, neutral spine throughout — avoid rounding or excessive arching of back; hinge from hips, not spine bend.\n* Use controlled movement — both while lifting (concentric) and lowering (eccentric); avoid jerking, swinging, or using momentum.\n* Elbow drive, not arm pull — focus on pulling with elbows close to body to maximize lat and upper-back activation rather than overusing biceps or forearms.\n* Appropriate weight selection — especially important if new to row or back training; heavy loads with poor form increase risk of lower-back injury or muscle imbalance.\nIf you have lower-back issues or poor hip mobility, consider easier variations (e.g. single-arm dumbbell row with one knee on bench, seated/cable rows, or other supported rowing exercises).",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult female, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "(What Back Rows Work)\n* Back muscles: Mainly Latissimus dorsi (lats), Rhomboids, and Trapezius (middle/lower), which generate the pulling motion and are responsible for upper-back width and thickness.\n* Posterior deltoids (rear shoulders) — engaged especially during the row’s retraction and scapular-retraction phases.\n* Stabilizers & supporting muscles: Lower back (spinal erectors), core muscles, glutes and hamstrings — to maintain torso position and stability during the bent-over posture.\n* Arms (to a lesser extent): Biceps and forearms contribute to grip and assist in pulling, but they are secondary to the back muscles.",
      "benefits": "Back Rows — Benefits\n* Effective for building back size (mass) and strength — back rows allow substantial loading and target large back muscles, contributing to thickness and a strong posterior chain.\n* Helps improve posture and spinal health — strengthening the posterior chain (back, glutes, spine-stabilizers) can alleviate back-pain risk, improve posture, and support day-to-day movements.\n* Functional pulling strength — helps in movements that require pulling force (lifting, carrying, climbing, daily tasks), not just aesthetic benefit.\n* Versatile — can be performed with barbell, dumbbells, or as supported (one-arm or bench-supported) rows depending on available equipment and user’s comfort / back health.",
      "safety": "/ Technique & Considerations\n* Maintain a flat, neutral spine throughout — avoid rounding or excessive arching of back; hinge from hips, not spine bend.\n* Use controlled movement — both while lifting (concentric) and lowering (eccentric); avoid jerking, swinging, or using momentum.\n* Elbow drive, not arm pull — focus on pulling with elbows close to body to maximize lat and upper-back activation rather than overusing biceps or forearms.\n* Appropriate weight selection — especially important if new to row or back training; heavy loads with poor form increase risk of lower-back injury or muscle imbalance.\nIf you have lower-back issues or poor hip mobility, consider easier variations (e.g. single-arm dumbbell row with one knee on bench, seated/cable rows, or other supported rowing exercises)."
