      "category": "arms",
      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — around 7–9 seconds long.\n* Resolution: 1920 × 1080 (Full HD), 24 fps.\n* Lighting: Gym or clean indoor lighting; neutral/minimal background to keep emphasis on shoulders and arm motion; soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight muscle definition and form.\n* Sound: Ambient (dumbbell movement, soft breathing), no voice-over (optional subtle inhale-exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym or home-gym area with dumbbells; enough space to stand with arms free, no clutter around.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or at waist height) capturing full body (head to feet) — to show stance, posture, arm motion, and shoulder symmetry.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts or gym pants), holding a dumbbell in each hand beside thighs, ready to start.\nAction / Beats (0–8 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position: Stand upright with feet about shoulder-width apart (knees soft). Dumbbells down by your sides, palms facing inwards (neutral grip), arms extended but not locked (slight bend in elbows), shoulders relaxed. Core engaged, spine neutral.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Slight bend in knees, engage core and glutes to stabilize torso; avoid leaning or using momentum.\n* 2–4 s — Raise / Concentric Phase: Exhale; raise both dumbbells out to the sides in a controlled arc (abduction at the shoulder), keeping arms slightly bent — lift until arms are roughly parallel to the floor (shoulder height). Elbows lead the motion, wrists follow.\n* 4–5 s — Peak / Hold: Pause ~0.2–0.5 s at the top — arms at shoulder-level, dumbbells steady, feel contraction in side deltoids (shoulders).\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly lower dumbbells back down to start position under control. Keep torso stable, avoid swinging.\n* 7–8 s — Reset / Ready: Arms down, posture upright, ready for next rep or clip end.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Side (Lateral) deltoid head — main target: responsible for lifting arms sideways, contributing to shoulder width / shoulder “cap” look.\n* Supporting muscles: Front and rear deltoid heads (to stabilize shoulder joint), upper-back stabilizers (to maintain posture), small stabilizer muscles around shoulder joint.\n* Core and trunk stabilizers: to keep torso steady and prevent momentum or swinging, improving isolation of the deltoid.\nBenefits & Why Use Shoulder Fly\n* Builds shoulder width and aesthetic deltoid shape by isolating the side deltoids — helps achieve broader, more balanced shoulders.\n* Functions as a single-joint isolation movement, which reduces involvement of larger muscle groups (like chest or back) — good for targeted shoulder development, especially after compound lifts.\n* Low equipment demand — only dumbbells (or similar light weights), minimal space — can be done at home or gym.\n* Helps improve shoulder stability and joint health, by strengthening the deltoid and stabilizer muscles, useful for preventing shoulder-related imbalance or injury.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips & Common Mistakes\n* Keep a slight bend in elbows — don’t lock the arms fully straight; helps reduce joint stress and maintain tension on deltoids.\n* Avoid swinging or using momentum — movement should come from shoulder joint abduction, not torso, hips, or back; maintain controlled motion throughout.\n* Use moderate/light weight — because deltoids are relatively small muscles; heavy weight often leads to form breakdown and involvement of non-target muscles (traps, upper back).\n* Do not raise arms above shoulder height — lifting beyond parallel risks shifting emphasis from deltoids to other muscles (traps) and increases shoulder-joint stress.\n* Keep core engaged and torso stable, spine neutral — avoid leaning or arching back to “help” lift.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
