      "id": "arms_weighted_bench_dip_male",
      "name": "Weighted Bench Dip",
      "gender": "male",
      "category": "arms",
      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — about 8–10 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym or home-gym setting, clean background (bench, floor, minimal clutter), soft key-light + ambient fill to clearly show body position, arm path, and weight.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (bench contact, weight/plate sound, breathing), no voice-over (or optional subtle inhale/exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Equipment: Two benches (or one bench + floor arrangement), a weight plate (or dumbbell) for added resistance.\n* Location: Gym floor or home gym with benches; stable surface; enough space to set benches at appropriate spacing.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or at waist-height) capturing body from head to heels — so you can see hands on bench, torso, legs extension, chest/shoulder line, and weight placement.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/training pants), ready to perform weighted bench dip.\nAction / Beats (0 s–~9/10 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position:\n\n* Place two benches parallel (or have one bench and feet on a stable surface) spaced so your feet can rest while hands are behind you on the first bench.\n* Sit on edge of bench, place palms on bench edge beside hips, fingers pointing forward. Extend legs and rest heels (or calves) on the second bench (or floor) to get into start position.\n* Place a weight plate (or dumbbell) securely on your lap (or between thighs) — this adds resistance. Keep torso upright, shoulders back/down, core engaged.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Engage core, glutes; ensure hands are firmly placed, fingers forward; keep elbows close to body; avoid shoulder shrugging; eyes forward. This ensures stability before dipping.\n* 2–4 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly bend elbows to lower your body, allowing hips to move down between your hands. Lower until elbows reach roughly 90-degree angle (or until upper-arm parallel to floor). Keep torso close to the bench, shoulders stable. Avoid letting shoulders drop below elbows excessively (risk for shoulder stress).\n* 4–5 s — Bottom / Pause: Brief pause (≈ 0.2–0.5 s) at bottom position — weight on lap stable, elbows bent, triceps stretched, torso steady. This accentuates muscle stretch and tension.\n* 5–7 s — Push / Concentric Phase: Exhale; push through palms to extend elbows and raise torso back to starting position. Use triceps (and supporting muscles) to lift; avoid using legs to “kick” upward — movement should come from arms.\n* 7–8/9 s — Lockout / Reset: Arms nearly extended (avoid full lockout if needed to maintain tension), torso upright, core & glutes tight — ready for next rep or fade-out of clip.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus (What Weighted Bench Dip Works)\n* Primary target: Triceps brachii — addition of weight increases load, promoting strength and hypertrophy.\n* Secondary muscles: Chest (especially lower pecs) and front shoulders (anterior deltoids) — because the body-position and dip motion also engage pressing and stabilizing muscles.\n* Stabilizers: Forearms and wrists (for grip), core and glutes (to stabilize torso and maintain posture), lower-body to a minor extent (legs hold position).\nWhy Use Weighted Bench Dip — Benefits\n* Allows progressive overload on a classic dip — once bodyweight bench dips become easy, added weight helps continue stimulating muscle growth and strength.\n* Provides strong triceps & arm development — since bench dips already focus on triceps, extra resistance accentuates the stimulus for hypertrophy or strength gains.\n* Relatively simple setup but effective — only benches and a plate/dumbbell needed; can be done in many gym or home settings.\nForm & Safety / Technique & Common Mistakes to Watch\n* Keep elbows close to body — avoid flaring them out; this ensures triceps do the work and reduces shoulder stress.\n* Do not go excessively deep — lowering too far (shoulders well below elbows) can put undue strain on shoulder joints, especially under added weight. Stop around when elbows form ~90° angle or just until upper-arm is parallel to floor.\n* Shoulders down & back, chest up — avoid rounding/slouching shoulders; maintain proper scapular position for joint health and leverage.\n* Use controlled tempo — both descent and ascent should be slow and controlled; avoid bouncing or relying on leg drive.\n* Appropriate load selection & safe setup — start with modest additional weight; ensure benches are stable; if using a plate on lap, make sure weight won’t slip; if possible have a spotter assist (especially when loading/unloading).",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "(What Weighted Bench Dip Works)\n* Primary target: Triceps brachii — addition of weight increases load, promoting strength and hypertrophy.\n* Secondary muscles: Chest (especially lower pecs) and front shoulders (anterior deltoids) — because the body-position and dip motion also engage pressing and stabilizing muscles.\n* Stabilizers: Forearms and wrists (for grip), core and glutes (to stabilize torso and maintain posture), lower-body to a minor extent (legs hold position).",
      "benefits": "Weighted Bench Dip — Benefits\n* Allows progressive overload on a classic dip — once bodyweight bench dips become easy, added weight helps continue stimulating muscle growth and strength.\n* Provides strong triceps & arm development — since bench dips already focus on triceps, extra resistance accentuates the stimulus for hypertrophy or strength gains.\n* Relatively simple setup but effective — only benches and a plate/dumbbell needed; can be done in many gym or home settings.",
      "safety": "/ Technique & Common Mistakes to Watch\n* Keep elbows close to body — avoid flaring them out; this ensures triceps do the work and reduces shoulder stress.\n* Do not go excessively deep — lowering too far (shoulders well below elbows) can put undue strain on shoulder joints, especially under added weight. Stop around when elbows form ~90° angle or just until upper-arm is parallel to floor.\n* Shoulders down & back, chest up — avoid rounding/slouching shoulders; maintain proper scapular position for joint health and leverage.\n* Use controlled tempo — both descent and ascent should be slow and controlled; avoid bouncing or relying on leg drive.\n* Appropriate load selection & safe setup — start with modest additional weight; ensure benches are stable; if using a plate on lap, make sure weight won’t slip; if possible have a spotter assist (especially when loading/unloading)."
