      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — ~ 7–9 seconds long.\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps.\n* Lighting & Color: Gym or home-gym floor, plain/neutral background, with lighting that highlights arms, barbell and forearm/upper-arm muscles. Soft key + fill lighting to make definition visible.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (barbell sound, floor noise, subtle breathing), no voice-over (optional gentle inhale/exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Equipment: Barbell (or EZ-curl bar), with appropriate weight; floor space for standing curl.\n* Location: Gym floor or home-gym; enough space for standing curls, stable footing.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or at about waist-height) capturing from head to thighs — so you can see full arm motion, bar path, posture, and elbow/forearm alignment.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic/average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts or training pants), gripping bar with overhand (pronated) grip, ready to curl.\nAction / Beats (0 s–~8/9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position: Stand with feet about shoulder-width apart. Grip barbell with palms facing down (overhand / pronated), hands around shoulder-width. Arms extended downward, bar hanging just in front of thighs. Keep torso upright, chest up, core and glutes slightly braced, elbows close to sides.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Slight bend in knees (optional), keep upper arms still; wrists straight (avoid bending), shoulders relaxed and stable. Focus on tight grip.\n* 2–4 s — Curl / Concentric Phase: Exhale; flex elbows and curl the bar upward — forearms lift toward shoulders/upper-arms, while keeping upper arms stationary at sides. Keep wrists neutral (not bending), bar path straight upward.\n* 4–5 s — Peak / Hold: Brief pause (≈ 0.2–0.4 s) at top — bar near shoulders or mid-biceps, forearms vertical, full contraction felt in forearms / brachialis / biceps. Shoulders stable, posture upright.\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly and controlled lower the bar back to starting position (arms extended), resisting gravity. Avoid dropping or letting momentum take over. Maintain posture and control.\n* 7–8/9 s — Reset / Ready: Arms extended downward, bar back at thighs, posture upright — ready for next rep or clip end.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus (What Reverse Barbell Curl Works)\n* Brachioradialis (forearm) — primary target; reverse (pronated) grip shifts emphasis to this forearm-flexor muscle, helping build forearm strength and thickness.\n* Brachialis (under-biceps) — elbow flexion is still required, so this muscle contributes significantly, helping push up biceps volume by developing underlying structure.\n* Biceps Brachii (to a lesser extent) — though less emphasized than in standard curls, biceps still contribute to arm flexion.\n* Grip & forearm extensors / stabilizers — strong grip engagement is required throughout movement due to pronated grip; helps improve wrist, forearm, and grip strength.\nBenefits & Why Use Reverse Barbell Curl\n* Builds forearm strength & grip strength — because of the pronated grip and focus on brachioradialis, it’s one of the most effective barbell exercises for forearms.\n* Enhances balanced arm development — working brachialis and brachioradialis adds depth and thickness to arms, which regular curls alone may under-develop.\n* Strengthens elbow flexors & wrist stability — useful for functional lifts (pull-ups, rows, deadlifts) where grip and forearm endurance matter.\n* Offers variation from standard curls — changing grip changes muscle recruitment; good to include periodically to avoid plateaus and improve overall arm strength.\nForm & Safety / Technique & Common Mistakes to Avoid\n* Keep upper arms stationary — do not let elbows swing forward or out; movement should only come from elbow flexion.\n* Maintain straight wrists — do not bend wrists during curl; bending can place stress on wrist tendons and reduce forearm activation.\n* Avoid using momentum — no swinging or “body jerk” to lift weight; use controlled tempo, especially on lowering phase to maximize muscle tension and avoid injury.\n* Use moderate weight — because grip and forearm muscles fatigue faster than biceps/larger muscles, start with lighter weights than standard curls; quality over load.\n* Proper posture — stand upright, core engaged, shoulders stable; avoid leaning back or using lower-body momentum.",
