      "muscles": "(What Reverse Barbell Curl Works)\n* Brachioradialis (forearm) — primary target; reverse (pronated) grip shifts emphasis to this forearm-flexor muscle, helping build forearm strength and thickness.\n* Brachialis (under-biceps) — elbow flexion is still required, so this muscle contributes significantly, helping push up biceps volume by developing underlying structure.\n* Biceps Brachii (to a lesser extent) — though less emphasized than in standard curls, biceps still contribute to arm flexion.\n* Grip & forearm extensors / stabilizers — strong grip engagement is required throughout movement due to pronated grip; helps improve wrist, forearm, and grip strength.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Reverse Barbell Curl\n* Builds forearm strength & grip strength — because of the pronated grip and focus on brachioradialis, it’s one of the most effective barbell exercises for forearms.\n* Enhances balanced arm development — working brachialis and brachioradialis adds depth and thickness to arms, which regular curls alone may under-develop.\n* Strengthens elbow flexors & wrist stability — useful for functional lifts (pull-ups, rows, deadlifts) where grip and forearm endurance matter.\n* Offers variation from standard curls — changing grip changes muscle recruitment; good to include periodically to avoid plateaus and improve overall arm strength.",
      "safety": "/ Technique & Common Mistakes to Avoid\n* Keep upper arms stationary — do not let elbows swing forward or out; movement should only come from elbow flexion.\n* Maintain straight wrists — do not bend wrists during curl; bending can place stress on wrist tendons and reduce forearm activation.\n* Avoid using momentum — no swinging or “body jerk” to lift weight; use controlled tempo, especially on lowering phase to maximize muscle tension and avoid injury.\n* Use moderate weight — because grip and forearm muscles fatigue faster than biceps/larger muscles, start with lighter weights than standard curls; quality over load.\n* Proper posture — stand upright, core engaged, shoulders stable; avoid leaning back or using lower-body momentum."
